reviewText: This film is a layered story (WWII in France and Germany seen through a group of 4 - 5 GIs) that hangs together despite some shortcomings. These include uneven acting, though some performances are fine. The film seems shot with a hand-held camera so much of the story is taken close in. I thought this more or less worked, overcoming the forced acting that occurs here and there. But I did feel that the scenes tended to get a bit claustrophobic after awhile. Cinematic rhythm requires a balance of close-ups, mid- and long-shots to register with the viewer.The script is solid, and does a good job in giving some humanity to the Germans when they appear, unlike the overpraised Saving Private Ryan which I felt became melodramatic and jingoistic in the second half. One of the more poignant scenes is the suicide of a devastated German infantryman at the end of the film. The director pulls back his camera to frame his fallen form and the helpless Sgt. Smith against a late afternoon lake. Thankfully, he holds us there, evoking honest emotion and compassion.The combat scenes of EW are quite intense and chaotic -- quickly edited, and I found this to be an asset overall. It conveyed the rush and confusion of infantry combat.Viewed at home, and for best effect, I recommend at least a 35 " screen with the volume set higher.
summary: honest, engaging  effort from a low budget

reviewText: Somehow I got the impression that this was a documentary about the Battle of the Bulge, but it turned out to be a feature film. It's a good one, but it's not a typical action packed war movie, it's about the characters in a squad, particularly Smith. You may be hoping for more explosions and shooting (I was in the mood for it), but it turns out to be a pretty good film. The only thing I have to complain about as being erroneous is that many of the characters were complaining about being drafted or being sent to war. At that time, EVERYONE wanted to do their part; EVERYONE wanted to join the military after Pearl Harbor. The only one that did not, and weaseled his way out, was Frank Sinatra and he was justly despised by many for his cowardice
summary: Not your usual shoot'em up war movie

reviewText: This movie is a excellent war movie. It's not the highest budget flick and it has many first time actors in it but it's better than some larger budget movies because it has a true story and alot of  heart to relie on.  The war wounds look convincing but you don't actually see men fly apart as a higher budget flick would show you.But that's fine because you understand how bad war can be and how most men just want it to end eventually.  That being said they are willing to stay and fight in what they believe in. The germans in this movie are depicted as human beings as well.  In fact the main narrator runs into a german soldier who has lost everything and everyone. Which would be quite common for many germans , and other europeons as well in those days.  Something we spoiled people of this century often don't try to grasp, destruction isn't a video game it has real consequencs.  The movie is a salute to the 94 inf and they never lost ground and served under the great general Patton. And the film looks great on dvd , with no aritifacts or other problems.This is a superior lower budget movie (but it's still well done enough that you won't notice)  by any standards and it's done so well and it does have a emotional punch as the now ederly soldier pines for his long dead friends at the end.

reviewText: The one star crowd is being far too harsh.  I suppose, once again, everybody's expecting Saving Private Ryan or Band of Brothers now with every war movie they watch - that isn't going to happen and thankfully, it shouldn't happen.This is a small budget Indy film that does start off VERY slow because it does a laborious job of building the backgrounds of the soldiers involved.  The older gent who doesn't "act" all that well is the ACTUAL veteran this movie is centered on, so for pity's sake, cut the man a little slack - he's not an actor, HE'S THE ACTUAL COMBAT VETERAN THIS MOVIE IS BASED ON!  I can forgive him for not being Leonardo Dicaprio in the role of playing himself.They actually do a VERY good job with this movie once it moves overseas and you actually get to the war.  Yes, there are a lot of "buddy" conversations, but you know what, there were a lot of buddy conversations during the war - it wasn't non-stop combat with sticking bayonets into the stomachs of everyone around you.  I will commend the film makers for portraying (for the first time I EVER remember seeing any) German Kriegsmarine coastal troops - yes, German Marines - never seen them portrayed in any war movie regardless of the budget.This isn't a bad movie, it tries to do a little too much and that's where it runs into some trouble, but if you are a WWII history buff, you'll like this movie - if you're not a WWII history buff, then you're not going to like this movie.  Personally, I liked it and will eventually watch it again.
summary: It's slow and low budget, but not a bad little movie here.

reviewText: "Everyman's War" is just that! It is based on the true story of Staff Sergeant Don Smith and his group of infantrymen during the Battle of the Bulge in 1944. This movie follows the men of the 9/4 Infantry in the snowy mountains near Nennig, Germany. They were up against the German 11th Panzer "Ghost" division but Don's group stood their ground. Throughout the film each soldier was introduced along with a little about his life before the war. The film gave a personal feel for each man and the families they left behind.  It also showed an update as to what became of them during the war as well as those who survived after the war. This film ranks among the best such as "Saving Private Ryan" and "Band of Brothers."

summary: Believable, well-done small unit war movie

reviewText: A truly bland, dull movie based on a 'true story' during the Battle of the Bulge in WW2.  A real life story in this movie's context is nonsense.  War situations could produce a million true stories of heroism and sacrifice but this isn't one of them.This is director Thad Smith's first attempt and it shows.  With a budget well under a million it means a poor script and plotting, mediocre acting (though some of them did their best) uneven sound recording, a complete absence of any color values with the various locations and wooden direction.  Because there was no real budget there are plenty of close-ups of the actors talking which relieves the art director from building too many sets.  The battle scenes are all seen from an individuals viewpoint so no broad scope of tanks and troops providing a visual backdrop for the close-up buddy stuff to be edited in.The script was the predictable war-time cliché chatter between buddies and for the first twenty or so minutes with their loved ones back home.  The actual plot was just so paper thin which meant that all the other shortcomings in the movie became even more apparent.Clearly one for the local charity shop.
